<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910930-0014</DOCNO><DOCID>910930-0014.</DOCID><HL>   Business Brief -- American Savings Bank:   Thrift Expects to Report   `Substantial' 3rd-Period Loss</HL><DATE>09/30/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B6</SO><CO>   ASB</CO><MS>FINANCIAL (FIN)</MS><IN>SAVINGS AND LOANS, THRIFTS (SAL)</IN><NS>EARNINGS PROJECTIONS (ERP)</NS><RE>NORTH AMERICA (NME)NEW YORK (NY)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   American Savings Bank, White Plains, N.Y., said it expectsto report a &quot;substantial&quot; loss for the third quarter.   The troubled thrift said the anticipated loss reflectedprovisions for possible loan and asset losses of between $55million and $60 million and charges of approximately $3million related to employee severance and other financialrestructuring activities.</LP><TEXT>   In the third quarter last year, American Savings reporteda loss of $6.4 million, or $1.29 a share.   W. Ronald Dietz, president and chief executive, said thethe third-quarter loss provisions will be used to coverreserves for nonperforming loans and write-downs on realestate recently foreclosed. He said the action also was takenfollowing inspections by federal and state bankingregulators.   Mr. Dietz said the third-quarter loss will increase theamount of capital American will need to meet regulatorystandards, however, programs &quot;of rigorous loan management, anorderly decrease in our asset base, strict expense controls,and modification of the bank's cumulative preferred stock arestill appropriate and are being pursued,&quot; he said.</TEXT></DOC>